00:05:14.510 --> 00:05:20.780
Last week, we told you about Respawn Entertainment's new
"Titanfall" first person shooter title set to use Valve's Source engine.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:22.940
While few details were available at the time,

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:25.880
a lot more information regarding the
game has surfaced in the past week

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:30.490
after the game was shown off multiple times at the
Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles,

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:33.910
which ran from Monday, June the 10th
until Wednesday, June the 13th.

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:39.300
The game's central mechanics revolve around the transition
between traditional on-ground first person shooting,

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:44.010
free running/parkour and large-scale mech
combat using robotic suits known as "Titans".

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:48.550
The Source engine's trademark facial animation
system was also on display during the reveal,

00:05:48.550 --> 00:05:51.130
even if it appeared strangely out of sync with the audio.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:53.820
While the game certainly shows a few of Source's minor wrinkles,

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:58.220
we were amazed at the level of visual fidelity
and scale possible on the decade-old engine,

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:02.060
even with the supposed next-gen changes
Respawn have allegedly been making.

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:06.050
Polygon's Aaron Gies reported on the design
decisions behind the engine choice,

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:08.780
which include the development team's familiarity with the engine

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:13.650
and the ability for Source to run smoothly at
60 frames per second on current generation consoles,

00:06:13.650 --> 00:06:16.160
something many other third party engines lack.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:21.950
If Respawn Entertainment's 65-person team is able to
make this kind of technical leap with the old Source engine,

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:27.450
color us excited to find out what Valve's own dedicated engineers
and programmers will be able to do with Source 2.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:30.890
We'll keep you posted with any further developments
regarding the current Source engine

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:33.170
or the upcoming next-gen Source 2.

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:36.150
That brings us to the end of another week of Valve news.

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:39.090
Don't forget to visit our website and to subscribe here on YouTube

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:42.640
